benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog/plan - Retrieve plan for a given subscription and date

covered: Valid requests: success scenarios for subscriptionId+requestedDate, only subscriptionId, only requestedDate, neither, boundary cases, and regression/compatibility (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC13, TC19, TC20).
Query parameters: wide coverage of combinations including valid, missing, malformed, non-existent, and extra parameters (TC01–TC08, TC14).
Empty / no-data handling: explicit tests for no matching plan and empty database (TC03, TC04, TC11).
Error handling: malformed inputs and not found responses and service errors are covered with expected HTTP status codes (400, 404, 409/500, 503) (TC05–TC08, TC10, TC12).
Security / input validation: SQL injection and XSS attempt tests present (TC17, TC18).
Performance: response time under normal and concurrent load included (TC15, TC16).
Authorization: unauthorized access (missing/invalid token) is tested (TC09).
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination or handling of large result sets (page/limit behaviors). If the endpoint may return multiple plans or lists, pagination is not covered.
Caching behavior: No scenarios validate caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control, Last-Modified) or conditional GET behavior (If-None-Match / 304 semantics).
Rate limiting / throttling: No tests exercise rate limits, 429 responses, or Retry-After behavior.
Response headers: No explicit assertions for Content-Type (application/json) or other important headers in success and error responses.
Authorization nuance: 403 Forbidden (valid auth but insufficient permissions) and role/scope based authorization tests are not present; only 401 is covered.
HTTP semantics: No tests for method-not-allowed (405) or content negotiation (Accept header variations).
recommendations: Add pagination tests if the API can return multiple plans: verify page/limit, boundary pages, total counts and behavior with large datasets; if pagination is not applicable, document this in the story so tests can mark it as N/A.
Add caching tests: assert presence and correctness of ETag and Cache-Control headers, and add conditional GET tests (If-None-Match) to confirm 304 responses when applicable.
Add rate limiting tests: simulate bursts and sustained high request rates to verify 429 responses and presence/value of Retry-After header, and verify graceful degradation under throttle.
Assert response headers explicitly in success and error cases (Content-Type: application/json, Content-Length when relevant, Cache-Control).
Extend authorization tests to cover 403 Forbidden (valid token but insufficient privileges) and any role/scope permutations if the API enforces finer-grained access control.
Add HTTP semantics tests: call the endpoint with disallowed methods to verify 405 Method Not Allowed, and test Accept header variations to confirm behavior for content negotiation.

If applicable, add tests for concurrency/race conditions where a plan could change during lookup (e.g., plan switch during retrieval) and for combinations of non-existent subscriptionId with dates to exercise more negative permutations.
Update the acceptance criteria / story if any guideline items (pagination, caching) are intentionally out of scope so the test suite and coverage assessment can treat them as not applicable.
